@node Compatibility Stubs and No-Op Calls
@section Compatibility Stubs and No-Op Calls

Several syscall numbers are accepted mainly to keep userland startup paths
happy.

@multitable @columnfractions .10 .20 .70
@headitem Nr @tab Name @tab Behavior
@item 10 @tab @code{mprotect} @tab Updates user-page presence and write
permissions for existing mappings.
@item 28 @tab @code{madvise} @tab Returns success.
@item 131 @tab @code{sigaltstack} @tab Stores and reports alternate-signal-stack
state, but signal delivery does not yet switch to it.
@item 157 @tab @code{prctl} @tab Supports task name, dumpable,
no-new-privs, and parent-death-signal state; a few Linux compatibility
subcommands are accepted as no-ops.
@item 202 @tab @code{futex} @tab Supports basic wait/wake operations with
timeouts and signal interruption.
@item 273 @tab @code{set_robust_list} @tab Stores robust-list metadata for the
current task.
@item 334 @tab @code{rseq} @tab Returns @code{ENOSYS}.
@end multitable

These calls are best understood as compatibility shims, not complete
subsystems.

@node Error Model and Semantic Caveats
@section Error Model and Semantic Caveats

The syscall layer returns Linux-style negative error numbers from the kernel
implementation.  Common values include @code{EINVAL}, @code{ENOENT},
@code{EBADF}, @code{EAGAIN}, @code{ENOSYS}, @code{EPIPE}, @code{ESRCH}, and
@code{ENOMEM}.

Important semantic caveats to remember:

@itemize @bullet
@item Filesystem mutation is limited to writable ext2/ext3 mounts, the
@file{/home} ramdisk fallback, and the @file{/tmp} ramdisk; the root initramfs
and shipped @file{/usr} are read-only.
@item @code{poll}, @code{select}, and @code{nanosleep} are not driven by a
preemptive timer interrupt.  Wall-clock time is seeded from RTC state when
available and then advanced from the TSC.
@item @code{clone} does not offer full Linux thread semantics.
@item @code{/proc} and @code{/sys} are not real filesystems.
@item @code{mprotect} enforces only coarse present/write page permissions; page
fault reporting is still primitive.
@item @code{futex}, @code{sigaltstack}, and @code{set_robust_list} implement
useful state and wait/wake behavior, but not the full Linux threading/runtime
contract.
@item Socket support includes pathname Unix-domain stream sockets and a small
IPv4 stack, but the Internet socket behavior is intentionally narrow and does
not provide complete Linux networking semantics.
@end itemize
